And depending on who I'm with I sort of the
accent sort of tends to change, but I grew

00:03:49.790 --> 00:03:56.350
up in the U.S., I grew up in Paris, in Brussels,
London, Hong Kong and also in China.

00:03:56.350 --> 00:03:59.680
So I think without knowing it my parents were
sort of getting me ready for this lifetime

00:03:59.680 --> 00:04:02.540
career of change, although I just didn't know
it at the time.

00:04:02.540 --> 00:04:07.569
But you get exposed to very different schools
and religious environments and cultures and

00:04:07.569 --> 00:04:12.290
food and you name it, you sort of get given
this sort of big trip into change.

00:04:12.290 --> 00:04:16.440
And even despite all the change that I've
been given what happened was that I tended

00:04:16.440 --> 00:04:19.910
to do what I would consider the safe route.

00:04:19.910 --> 00:04:24.130
So I went to college, I went to the London
School of Economics, graduated first in my

00:04:24.130 --> 00:04:26.400
class, did what I thought was expected of
me.

00:04:26.400 --> 00:04:28.960
So I had this sort of big should program on
me.

00:04:28.960 --> 00:04:30.210
I should study hard.

00:04:30.210 --> 00:04:31.900
I should go to college.

00:04:31.900 --> 00:04:33.770
I should go to certain companies.

00:04:33.770 --> 00:04:37.370
So the next should was to go into management
consulting.

00:04:37.370 --> 00:04:40.560
I studied economics and it felt like it was
just the right next thing to do.

00:04:40.560 --> 00:04:45.290
So I joined The Boston Consulting Group and
did a couple years with them.

00:04:45.290 --> 00:04:48.660
They sent me all around the world, which made
that experience a little bit easier for me.

00:04:48.660 --> 00:04:51.380
But I always kind of had an inkling that something
wasn't quite right.

00:04:51.380 --> 00:04:54.930
I kind of knew that it wasn't really what
I was here to be doing.

00:04:54.930 --> 00:04:58.650
I sort of shut that voice down for a little
while longer, then I came out here and I went

00:04:58.650 --> 00:04:59.650
to business school.

00:04:59.650 --> 00:05:04.690
So I went to Stanford and you know that was
sort of an amazing experience, but I kept

00:05:04.690 --> 00:05:06.960
on sort of saying you know what should I do
with my life?

00:05:06.960 --> 00:05:10.120
That was sort of the big lingering question
in the background.

00:05:10.120 --> 00:05:14.750
And I traipsed off to New York City after
that and I spent ten years in the media world.

00:05:14.750 --> 00:05:19.310
And I worked at Bertelsmann, I worked at Sony,
I worked at Time/Warner.

00:05:19.310 --> 00:05:22.620
And as you can tell I was jumping around a
lot and I kept on trying to sort of figure

00:05:22.620 --> 00:05:26.610
out what is, what is actually right, what,
what am I meant to be doing with my life?

00:05:26.610 --> 00:05:32.970
And I landed at Time/Warner at the age of
28/29 in charge of a $500 million venture

00:05:32.970 --> 00:05:34.240
capital fund.

00:05:34.240 --> 00:05:39.880
And I was managing director of this fund and
I was you know supposedly had climbed this

00:05:39.880 --> 00:05:44.350
very high ladder, but I had the sense that
it was the wrong ladder and it was definitely

00:05:44.350 --> 00:05:46.480
leaning up against the wrong wall.

00:05:46.480 --> 00:05:51.060
And even though I had this semblance of a
very perfect sort of external life, what started

00:05:51.060 --> 00:05:56.590
happening was that inner microphone that you
all have started going off pretty loudly.

00:05:56.590 --> 00:06:03.630
And the inner microphone sounds like this,
"Ariane, you're in the wrong job."

00:06:03.630 --> 00:06:05.280
That was the first inner microphone.

00:06:05.280 --> 00:06:09.910
The second inner microphone was, "Ariane,
you're sleeping with the wrong guy."

00:06:09.910 --> 00:06:11.949
[audience laughter] That was the second one.

00:06:11.949 --> 00:06:16.410
And I thought, how is it possible that I've
set up this perfect life and none of it's

00:06:16.410 --> 00:06:18.710
right and all of it needs to now change.

00:06:18.710 --> 00:06:23.229
So I was about 30/31 and it's a long story,
but I eventually had the courage to leave

00:06:23.229 --> 00:06:24.860
that job.

00:06:24.860 --> 00:06:26.630
And I actually had no idea what was gonna
come next.

00:06:26.630 --> 00:06:31.009
I was sort of in that void and in between
careers and couldn't quite see what, what

00:06:31.009 --> 00:06:32.229
was coming.

00:06:32.229 --> 00:06:36.259
And so what I did was I started getting really
honest with myself.

00:06:36.259 --> 00:06:38.650
What was the number one thing that was missing
for me?

00:06:38.650 --> 00:06:40.930
And it was the sense that I wasn't really
making a difference.

00:06:40.930 --> 00:06:44.240
I wasn't really adding value, I wasn't really
contributing.

00:06:44.240 --> 00:06:45.530
And it's interesting.

00:06:45.530 --> 00:06:49.759
If you look at like all the research now going
on in the U.S., the number one reason people

00:06:49.759 --> 00:06:55.349
are unhappy at work and people in general
have this sense of slight depression, you

00:06:55.349 --> 00:07:00.069
know Gallup Poll did a poll recently where
more than two-thirds of employees are unhappy

00:07:00.069 --> 00:07:01.069
in their work.

00:07:01.069 --> 00:07:04.000
And the number one reason is because people
don't feel that they're actually adding value.

00:07:04.000 --> 00:07:06.229
So I was feeling that big time.

00:07:06.229 --> 00:07:10.370
And so I did what I knew best, which is I
went off and I went traveling.

00:07:10.370 --> 00:07:12.890
And I started asking myself very different
questions.

00:07:12.890 --> 00:07:18.000
So instead of creating this externally perfect
life, I sort of turned my entire focus inwards

00:07:18.000 --> 00:07:20.780
and I started asking very internal questions.

00:07:20.780 --> 00:07:22.740
What's worth doing with this life?

00:07:22.740 --> 00:07:24.620
What does Ariane want to do?

00:07:24.620 --> 00:07:30.380
Not my parents, not what was expected of me,
not, not sort of all this external conditioning,

00:07:30.380 --> 00:07:31.380
what I call the tribe.

00:07:31.380 --> 00:07:34.690
Where the tribe has sort of told you what
is expected of you.

00:07:34.690 --> 00:07:39.099
And it was while I was traveling I sort of
had this one question to life.

00:07:39.099 --> 00:07:40.190
Show me the way.

00:07:40.190 --> 00:07:41.190
Show me the way.

00:07:41.190 --> 00:07:42.190
Show me what's next.

00:07:42.190 --> 00:07:43.330
Show me what I'm meant to be doing.

00:07:43.330 --> 00:07:47.669
And I sort of walked around a few different
countries with sort of antenna on my head.

00:07:47.669 --> 00:07:52.870
And I was just looking for signs and synchronicities
and things that could give me a clue.

00:07:52.870 --> 00:07:58.400
And what I realized was that every single
person I was meeting was in one of three categories

00:07:58.400 --> 00:08:00.630
and all of you are in this as well.

00:08:00.630 --> 00:08:03.780
They were either going through some sort of
a change.

00:08:03.780 --> 00:08:08.400
They were either thinking about making a change,
but had some sort of excuse or something going

00:08:08.400 --> 00:08:09.639
on in the way.

00:08:09.639 --> 00:08:11.520
Or they were helping someone with a change.

00:08:11.520 --> 00:08:15.889
So it was a spouse or a friend or a partner
or a child or a colleague.

00:08:15.889 --> 00:08:19.390
And then I found out later through I was giving
a speech somewhere else and someone said,

00:08:19.390 --> 00:08:20.390
no, there's a fourth category.

00:08:20.390 --> 00:08:21.699
And I was like, bring it on.

00:08:21.699 --> 00:08:26.240
And the fourth category, which some of us
are all guilty of, is we're waiting for someone

00:08:26.240 --> 00:08:28.169
else to change, not us.

00:08:28.169 --> 00:08:31.240
[audience laughter] We're waiting for someone
else to change, it has nothing to do with

00:08:31.240 --> 00:08:32.240
us.

00:08:32.240 --> 00:08:35.260
But it was interesting that this change thing
was all around me.

00:08:35.260 --> 00:08:37.170
And I met people who were, had gotten divorced.

00:08:37.170 --> 00:08:40.130
And I met people who had just you know lost
a parent.

00:08:40.130 --> 00:08:43.580
And I met people who had just found out their
child was autistic.

00:08:43.580 --> 00:08:46.020
And I met people who were getting through
depression.

00:08:46.020 --> 00:08:48.270
And I met people who had just lost their job.

00:08:48.270 --> 00:08:51.780
But it was like this change thing was all
around me and I thought, isn't it interesting

00:08:51.780 --> 00:08:54.940
that change is the number one guarantee in
life.

00:08:54.940 --> 00:08:58.930
JFK said it's the law of life, and yet no
one knows how to go through it.

00:08:58.930 --> 00:09:02.320
And I thought there must be ways to make change
easier.

00:09:02.320 --> 00:09:04.580
Like we, we're all going through it.

00:09:04.580 --> 00:09:08.830
I personally believe it's the most important
life skill to get good at.

00:09:08.830 --> 00:09:11.650
As parents we protect our kids from change.

00:09:11.650 --> 00:09:13.840
We definitely do not throw them into change.

00:09:13.840 --> 00:09:15.910
The less change, the more stable.

00:09:15.910 --> 00:09:20.310
The more calm the more you think you're doing
your kids a favor, which is not the case.

00:09:20.310 --> 00:09:24.910
And as adults we walk into the world and we're
thrown with so much change and we actually

00:09:24.910 --> 00:09:28.470
don't have the skills to sort of navigate
it.

00:09:28.470 --> 00:09:32.940
So what I sort of started thinking was what
happens if I interviewed people and just sort

00:09:32.940 --> 00:09:37.600
of started listening to why is it that you're
good at change and someone else has a really

00:09:37.600 --> 00:09:38.710
hard time?

00:09:38.710 --> 00:09:42.540
Why is it that some of you are thinking about
a change and others of you have actually gone

00:09:42.540 --> 00:09:43.540
on and done that?

00:09:43.540 --> 00:09:48.160
And it was fascinating to me that some of
us were naturally good at change and others

00:09:48.160 --> 00:09:49.160
weren't.

00:09:49.160 --> 00:09:50.390
Were men better at change than women?

00:09:50.390 --> 00:09:53.770
So it sort of, it sort of descended on me
it's like just go research this.

00:09:53.770 --> 00:09:57.670
It wasn't sort of, this is your next job or
this is what you're gonna be meant to be doing

00:09:57.670 --> 00:09:58.850
with your life.

00:09:58.850 --> 00:10:02.320
And so I started interviewing people and I
found, in effect, that there were ways to

00:10:02.320 --> 00:10:04.210
make change easier.

00:10:04.210 --> 00:10:09.210
So what I wanted to do is, I'm gonna take
you through these nine principles.

00:10:09.210 --> 00:10:15.750
What I did eventually was I did write a book
about it, right over here, The First 30 Days.

00:10:15.750 --> 00:10:20.790
I called it The First 30 Days because I wanted
people to get a sense that it just it takes

00:10:20.790 --> 00:10:27.010
more than just sort of the action plan or
the three things to do or you know here is

00:10:27.010 --> 00:10:30.980
how you start a business, here is how you
leave a job you don't like.

00:10:30.980 --> 00:10:34.850
There's actually sort of emotions that you
need to actually go through when you go through

00:10:34.850 --> 00:10:35.850
change.

00:10:35.850 --> 00:10:39.560
I started a website as well that goes with
it first30days.com.

00:10:39.560 --> 00:10:44.840
But what I wanted to say before I take you
through the nine principles, three things.

00:10:44.840 --> 00:10:49.220
Most of us when we think about change we think
about external changes.

00:10:49.220 --> 00:10:51.140
When we're gonna meet the soul mate.

00:10:51.140 --> 00:10:52.140
When we're gonna get married.

00:10:52.140 --> 00:10:53.140
When we're gonna have kids.

00:10:53.140 --> 00:10:55.250
When we're gonna have the big promotion.

00:10:55.250 --> 00:10:59.810
The most effective and the most important
changes you will ever make in your life are

00:10:59.810 --> 00:11:02.070
internal changes.

00:11:02.070 --> 00:11:03.640
Changes about how you see yourself.

00:11:03.640 --> 00:11:05.770
Changes about your identity.

00:11:05.770 --> 00:11:08.670
Changes about who you decide to forgive.

00:11:08.670 --> 00:11:11.670
Changes about who you decide to get honest
with.

00:11:11.670 --> 00:11:16.621
Internal changes, the identity of who you
are and who you see yourself to be, those

00:11:16.621 --> 00:11:18.960
are the changes that change everything.

00:11:18.960 --> 00:11:21.640
It's not when the external changes happen.

00:11:21.640 --> 00:11:25.600
You're gonna see that through the nine principles
that came out very, very strongly.

00:11:25.600 --> 00:11:30.030
The second thing is change is all about getting
comfortable with the unknown.

00:11:30.030 --> 00:11:35.160
It's not about clinging to here's how it's
gonna be or here's how someone else's experience

00:11:35.160 --> 00:11:36.820
was and that's what it's gonna be.

00:11:36.820 --> 00:11:41.180
It's all about getting comfortable with that
void of actually not knowing how it's gonna

00:11:41.180 --> 00:11:42.200
be.

00:11:42.200 --> 00:11:48.060
And the third thing is the very best of who
you are comes out during times of change.

00:11:48.060 --> 00:11:52.160
It does not come out when everything is really
certain and perfect.

00:11:52.160 --> 00:11:56.220
The very, your core essence is actually to
go through changes.

00:11:56.220 --> 00:11:59.680
When you're comfortable, that's when life
feels quite dull.

00:11:59.680 --> 00:12:03.750
When you're actually going through things,
that's when like there's life force, there's

00:12:03.750 --> 00:12:05.710
juice that's actually coming through you.

00:12:05.710 --> 00:12:10.590
So the invitation is to sort of you know give
you a sense of well, where are you on the

00:12:10.590 --> 00:12:12.060
change spectrum?

00:12:12.060 --> 00:12:15.210
So to do that I'm just gonna throw out a few
questions whether you wanna ask them in your

00:12:15.210 --> 00:12:19.830
head or write them down is sort of up to you,
but, and I do this with all the groups I talk

00:12:19.830 --> 00:12:20.880
to.

00:12:20.880 --> 00:12:24.910
The first question is, naturally, do you think
you are good at change?

00:12:24.910 --> 00:12:26.690
Yes or no?

00:12:26.690 --> 00:12:27.690
What comes up?

00:12:27.690 --> 00:12:29.050
Are you, are you a change optimist?

00:12:29.050 --> 00:12:32.930
Do you move towards change or you're like
I'm so not a change person?

00:12:32.930 --> 00:12:36.900
If things never change I'd be much happier
the way it is.

00:12:36.900 --> 00:12:43.390
Second question, do you feel you are better
at making changes or at facing changes that

00:12:43.390 --> 00:12:44.550
come your way?

00:12:44.550 --> 00:12:48.910
Are you one that naturally goes after a new
change or are you actually really good when

00:12:48.910 --> 00:12:52.290
life just goes handle it, deal with it?

00:12:52.290 --> 00:12:55.000
Because it's two very different types of people.

00:12:55.000 --> 00:12:57.940
You know most people can kind of go I'm really
good at change and they're really good in

00:12:57.940 --> 00:12:59.000
the crisis.

00:12:59.000 --> 00:13:03.040
But if you actually asked them what are changes
they'd love to make, they don't go close to

00:13:03.040 --> 00:13:04.040
them.

00:13:04.040 --> 00:13:05.690
That's the second question.

00:13:05.690 --> 00:13:09.560
Third question, just to give you a sense of
what I call your change history.

00:13:09.560 --> 00:13:15.540
You know, the core of who you are, are all
the changes you've ever made, been through,

